in the Ward]（公益財団法人 大倉精神文化研究所）</ref>. In addition, the local ''History of Kohoku Ward'' mentions that the “Mori” in the Mori family is derived from the “guardian forest” ({{ill|Sacred Grove|ja|鎮守の森|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sacred Grove|qq=}}) and that the family is locally reverenced as “Sugiyama-sama”. Moreover, nearby in Hayabuchi 3-chōme there exist the [[{{ill|North River Upper Ruins|ja|北川表の上遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/North River Upper Ruins|qq=}}]] and [[{{ill|North River Shell Mound|ja|北川貝塚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/North River Shell Mound|qq=}}]], and the ''Newly Compiled Musashi Fudoki Manuscript, Yoshida Village'' records that “a large shell mound existed in Yoshida Village of Tsuzuki District” {{sfn|Newly Compiled Musashi Fudoki Manuscript, Yoshida Village}}, with the local name “Shell Mound Field” still in use – evidence that archaeological sites in the area have long been known.<ref name="tsugaruoukoku-sugiyama"/> 

Like many other ronsya, the shrine is situated on an elevated spot along the {{ill|Tsurumi River|ja|鶴見川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsurumi River|qq=}} of the {{ill|water system|ja|水系|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/water system|qq=}} ({{ill|Hayabuchi River|ja|早渕川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hayabuchi River|qq=}}).

